@realmoney I Decided to Fade The Afternoon Strength This afternoon I elected to move to a medium- sized net short exposure. I recognize the risk of a market structure that favors "buyers buy higher (and sellers sell lower)" but the bad breadth to me may be seen as a short term

"tell" as could the narrowness of the leadership become more worrisome. We are getting more deeply overbought (especially the Nasdaq) and look at the McLellan Oscillator (see Mark B's comment We have moved definitively towards the higher end of my expected trading range

(2550-2950). With spot S&P at about 2930 and though we are only about 4% above my "fair market value" of 2800 -- I am practicing what I preach and what I write! @tomkeene @jimcramer @cnbcfastmoney @SquawkCNBC

That said, Twitter is a great platform to communicate, on a real-time basis, ideas and views. But it is so tough and cumbersome to sort out the wheat from the chaff.
Twitter is one of the few platforms where trolls without any history of investment or trading success try to convince oneself and others that he is the next Paul Tudor Jones.
Twitter is one of the few platforms where critics can attack extensive financial analysis with a phrase and without using one's real name. Truly remarkable.

Twitter is one of the few platforms where one can crow and sound quite glib (as if they got the market's direction correct) but, in actuality, have been wrong for over 700 S&P handles in the last two months. Truly remarkable.

The @realdonaldtrump 2020 "No Apologies Tour" continues: Two members of the White House staff tested positive for the coronavirus last week: Katie Miller (Press Secretary to Mike Pence) and an unnamed valet to Trump. The coronavirus has made its way into the White House.

See NYTimes, ‘Scary to Go to Work’: White House Races to Contain Virus in Its Ranks.” (“With two White House staff members testing positive, some officials fear the disease is already spreading rapidly through the West Wing.”) The last thing the country needs is a presidential

succession crisis caused by the grossly negligent actions of those surrounding Trump and Pence. But, over the weekend, those surrounding the president and vice-president refused to wear masks because Trump believes it signals weakness. See AP, Face masks make a political

statement in era of coronavirus. (“Trump has told advisers that he believes wearing one would “send the wrong message,” according to one administration and two campaign officials not authorized to publicly discuss private conversations.”) In failing to stand up to Trump’s

vanity, those government officials are engaging in unforgivable acts of cowardice that breach their duties to the American people. Take a look at this official tweet from White House showing Trump in a crowded meeting with the nation’s top military officers, the Secretary of

State, and the Secretary of Treasury (the latter two are in the line of presidential succession). This is what cowardice looks like—military men (no women) who are afraid to protect their Commander-in-Chief from a virus that has made its way into the White House. See CNN, “Trump

meets with military leaders. No one wears a mask.” To similar effect was a meeting Trump held with GOP leaders on Friday. See NBCNews, “No masks and little social distancing at White House meeting, despite two aides testing positive for virus.” Compare the cowardice of our

assembled military leaders afraid to protect Trump from the coronavirus with this iconic photo of Speaker Pelosi standing up to the president with many of the same men sitting mutely beside Trump. These concerns are not idle speculation. The following key government officials

are now in self-quarantine because of exposure in the White House: The Chief of Naval Operations, Dr. Fauci, Senator Lamar Alexander, and two other members of the Coronavirus Task Force. Although Mike Pence’s press secretary tested positive, Pence will report to work as usual.

See CNN, “Pence will not self-quarantine and plans to be at the White House Monday.” There is no rational explanation for Pence’s decision to risk spreading the coronavirus in the White House, so let me offer an irrational one. Pence believes he has been called by God to be
president. I’ll let you complete the thought . . . @tomkeene @jimcramer @riskreversal @ScottWapnerCNBC @andrewrsorkin @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney

reason Trump is engaging in such desperate measures is because he is losing. Worse—for Trump—is that these very tactics are the reason he is losing. Yet, he is incapable of learning from his failures. His rage-tweeting over the weekend is a perfect example. Trump has been engaged

in a “pity party” of immense proportions about the Mueller investigation as Americans are dying of a pandemic he failed to contain. Empathy for the suffering of the American people is an issue that is neither red nor blue. It is a matter of human emotion, respect, and humility—

all concepts alien to Trump. As things get worse, remember that Trump’s desperation is a sign of our progress in bringing about his defeat in November 2020. It is difficult to believe it can get worse, but it will. @andrewrsorkin @ScottWapnerCNBC @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC

The @realdonaldtrump 2020 "No Apologies Tour": As Trump begins to sense that he may lose in November, his actions are becoming desperate. He is gambling with the lives of Americans in the vain hope that a miraculous economic recovery will save his presidency. It won’t happen.

He is attempting to shift blame for his pathetic pandemic response to China. It won’t work. He is vilifying Robert Mueller, the FBI, Barak Obama, and the US intelligence community for proving that Russia interfered in our 2016 presidential election. It will do nothing to make

America more secure. None of Trump’s gambits will help America deal with its most urgent crisis in a generation. That’s his point. His meager abilities have been overwhelmed by a foe he cannot comprehend, so he has reverted to his only skill: attack without regard to logic or

sense or decency. It is a strategy of desperation for a candidate with the vast advantages of incumbency, a compliant Department of Justice, a rubber-stamp Supreme Court, and a Republican Party held hostage by Trump’s base. With the seasoning of seventy-two hours, it is clear

that the initial outraged reaction to dismissal of charges against Flynn was too restrained by an order of magnitude. In dismissing charges against Flynn, Trump and Barr said, in effect, “This is war.” Indeed, Bill Barr said as much in an interview last Friday when he smugly said

he wasn’t worried about history’s judgment of his actions because “History is written by the winners.” There you have it: Barr admitting that he is a partisan warrior for Trump—when he is supposed to be a neutral advocate for justice. But Barr is wrong. History is being written

today—and it is not kind to Bill Barr. See Vox, “11 legal experts agree: There’s no good reason for DOJ to drop the Michael Flynn case.” (“This is a pardon disguised as a technical legal matter.”), and Philip Rotner in The Bulwark, “Bill Barr Wants Us to Pretend Flynn’s Lies

Don’t Matter.” (Rotner’s analysis is an excellent guide for those of you who want to follow the legal analysis.) The fact that once-respected men like Barr have tied their fates to Trump proves that they, too, are desperate. They know Trump was a mistake of Biblical proportions,

but they have supported him thus far, and lack the backbone to walk away while Trump still holds the reins of power. I am not merely railing against Trump; I have a point: We must steel ourselves because it is going to get worse. Trump hinted as much on Sunday when he tweeted

over a hundred times!!! See The Independent, “Trump tweets more than 100 times in one day as coronavirus death toll nears 80,000.” Trump said that we should expect a “bombshell” this week. Without knowing anything more, I expect that Bill Barr’s hand-crafted investigation of the

FBI’s Russia probe will result in charges against someone in the FBI or DOJ for leaking to the press, perhaps James Comey. Or perhaps Barr will seek to undermine other criminal prosecutions by Mueller. On the one hand, all of this enough to drive us mad. On the other hand, the
